@page "/"

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- HERO -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="hero">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h1>Ripple Aquaponics</h1>
        <p>
            A conceptual model exploring how sustainable, community‑focused food systems 
            could support Chicago‑area neighborhoods year‑round.
        </p>

        <div class="hero-buttons">
            <a href="/about" class="btn primary">Learn More</a>
            <a href="/get-involved" class="btn secondary">Get Involved</a>
            <a href="/donate" class="btn donate">Donate (Demo)</a>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- PROBLEM SECTION -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="problem">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2>The Challenge</h2>
        <p>
            Many Chicago‑area neighborhoods experience limited access to fresh produce, rising food costs, 
            and harsh seasonal conditions that make year‑round growing difficult. This project uses 
            Chicagoland as a case study to explore how sustainable systems like aquaponics could help 
            address these challenges.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- HOW RIPPLE WORKS -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="how-it-works">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2>How Ripple Works (Conceptual Model)</h2>

        <div class="steps">
            <div class="step">
                <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-fish"></i> 1. We raise fish.</h3>
                <p>
                    In the modeled system, Nile tilapia produce nutrient‑rich waste that forms the basis 
                    of plant growth. This reflects real aquaponic practices.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="step">
                <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-leaf"></i> 2. We grow plants.</h3>
                <p>
                    Buttercrisp lettuce and other leafy greens are used as examples of crops that thrive 
                    in aquaponic environments. These crops are part of the conceptual design only.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="step">
                <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-hand-holding-heart"></i> 3. We feed the community.</h3>
                <p>
                    In this project model, produce and fish are imagined as being distributed through 
                    food pantries and community partners. This distribution network is hypothetical and 
                    included to demonstrate how a real nonprofit might operate.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-coral"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- WHY AQUAPONICS -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="why-aquaponics">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2>Why Aquaponics?</h2>
        <p>
            Aquaponics is a closed‑loop system that recycles water, conserves resources, and produces 
            nutrient‑dense food efficiently. This project uses aquaponics as a framework to explore 
            sustainable, scalable solutions for urban food systems.
        </p>

        <ul class="benefits">
            <li><i class="fa-solid fa-calendar"></i> Operates year‑round in controlled environments</li>
            <li><i class="fa-solid fa-droplet"></i> Uses significantly less water and land</li>
            <li><i class="fa-solid fa-truck"></i> Reduces reliance on long‑distance supply chains</li>
            <li><i class="fa-solid fa-seedling"></i> Provides predictable, high‑quality harvests</li>
            <li><i class="fa-solid fa-people-group"></i> Supports community education and engagement</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</section>

<div class="divider-blue"></div>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- MISSION -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="mission">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2>Our Mission (Conceptual)</h2>
        <p>
            Ripple imagines a future where sustainable food systems are accessible, community‑driven, 
            and environmentally responsible. This project models how aquaponics could support local 
            resilience and education.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- COMMUNITY FIRST -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="community">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2>Community First (Conceptual)</h2>
        <p>
            In this project, Ripple is imagined as a community‑driven effort where volunteers, students, 
            and researchers collaborate to support sustainable food systems. These roles are hypothetical 
            and included to demonstrate how community engagement might look in a real implementation.
        </p>

        <a href="/get-involved" class="btn primary">Get Involved</a>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- CTA SECTION -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="cta">
    <div class="section-inner">
        <h2>Help Us Grow the Ripple Effect</h2>
        <p>
            This project highlights the potential of sustainable, community‑focused food systems. 
            Explore the site to learn more about the model, the research behind it, and how a real 
            nonprofit could bring these ideas to life.
        </p>

        <div class="cta-buttons">
            <a href="/donate" class="btn donate">Donate (Demo)</a>
            <a href="/get-involved" class="btn secondary">Volunteer (Conceptual)</a>
            <a href="/about" class="btn primary">Learn More</a>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>
